\begin_layout Subsection
Identifying
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Interest rate risk
\series default
: the risk of the bond price declining, as a result of an increase in market
 interest rate (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

parallel shift
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the yield curve).
 It is important if the bond might not be held until maturity.
 If the intention is to hold until maturity - it is less important (though
 the bond would still appear on financial statements).
 The interest rate risk (sensitivity)is affected by:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Maturity: the longer the maturity, the greater the sensitivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Coupon rate: the lower it is, the greater the sensitivity (extreme case:
 a zero-coupon bond).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Embedded options: usually reduce the sensitivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Yield curve: the higher the yield curve in the market, the lower the sensitivity
 to changes in interest.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Reinvestment risk
\series default
: YTM assumes cash flow is 
\series bold
reinvested
\series default
.
 In reality, they may have to be reinvested at a lower interest rate.
 It is greater for amortizing bond.
 The risk is 0 for zero-coupon bond (e.g a T-bill).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Yield curve risk
\series default
: a non-parallel change shift (flattening, twist, steepening) of a yield
 curve imposes a risk - particularly important for MBS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Spread risk
\series default
: the risk that the spread (nominal / z-spread / OAS) over the corresponding
 T-bond would increase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Volatility risk
\series default
: higher future volatility increases the value of the embedded option.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Prepayment risk
\series default
: for call-embedded options, higher prepayment is made when the interest
 rate is lower than coupon rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Cap and floor risk
\series default
: the risk of a floating-rate security to hit the cap (floor) and not have
 full adjust in price.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Exchange-rate risk
\series default
: when investing in a foreign currency, the return in domestic currency
 depends on the exchange rate (currency appreciation / depreciation).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Inflation risk
\series default
: the risk of the decline in purchasing power due to inflation.
 TIPS are a simple way to eliminate it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Model risk
\series default
: the chance of the model being not good enough.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Liquidity risk
\series default
: the investor might have to sell the bond below its book value.
 It is indicated by the bid-ask spread (if there is aa big liquidity risk,
 a significant difference in the prices is to be compensated by the broker).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Event risk
\series default
: natural disaster, political risk, etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Settlement risk
\series default
: the probability of one party to pay, while the other one would default
 (mitigation: delivery instead of payment).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Regulatory and legal risk
\series default
: changes in regulations and their enforcement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Sovereign bonds risks
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Economic risk
\series default
 (growth, stability, fiscal responsibility, balance of payments)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Political risk
\series default
 (stability, governance)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Credit risk
\series default
: the risk of not paying on time.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Default risk
\series default
: the issuer might fail to fully pay the debt on time (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

last stage
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Credit spread risk
\series default
: the spread is perceived higher by investors, though there is no 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

default
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 yet.
 Only the idiosyncratic risk has increased.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Downgrade risk
\series default
: even a step before - downgrade by credit rating agencies.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
