\begin_layout Subsection
Measuring Risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have 
\series bold
identified
\series default
 risks (qualitative analysis), the next step is to 
\series bold
measure 
\series default
them (quantitative analysis), in order to be able to manage them.
 A crucial concept in this context is the 
\series bold
value at risk
\series default
 (
\series bold
VAR
\series default
) - an estimate of the minimum expected loss over a particular time period,
 at a desired significance level.
 For example, a 5% VAR of $1,000 means that (at least) a $1,000 lost is
 expected at 5% probability (and 95% confidence in the loss being less than
 $1,000).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Convexity
\series default
 refers to the non-linear relationship between the value of a security and
 its yield.
 The convexity is positive (negative) when for a given interest rate change,
 the capital loss effect is smaller (greater) than the gain effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Macaulay duration
\series default
: a time-weighted average until teh cash flow repays its price.
 Measures how long it taked for the bond to be repaid by its internal CF.
 Longer duration implies higher risk.
 A zero-coupon bond has duration equal to its time to maturity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
modified duration
\series default
 measures the sensitivity of a bond's price to a 
\series bold
parallel
\series default
 interest rate changes of 1% (assuming its CF do not change).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
dollar duration
\series default
 is the price change due to 1% change in the yield.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
spread duration
\series default
 measures the price sensitivity to a change in a spread (nominal / z-spread
 / OAS).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Managing Risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hedging based on a duration framework assumes a parallel yield curve shift.
 The first thing in risk management is putting a cap (positon limit) on
 an investment, in order to limit the risk exposure.
 A liquidity limit and performance stop-out might also be applicable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Managing the credit risk includes limiting the exposure, applying collaterals,
 derivatives and various standards.
\end_layout

